PostTask`, etc. for Claude, Gemini, and Factory Droid. It constructs fake transcripts and manually orchestrates the full session lifecycle step by step.\\n\\n- **E2E `TestEnv`** is a thinner wrapper. It has `RunAgent(prompt)` which delegates to the real agent binary and `RunEntireEnable(strategy)` which calls the actual `entire enable` CLI command. It doesn't import internal packages — it exercises the system purely through the CLI binary and agent subprocesses.\\n\\n### 4. What They Test\\n\\n**Integration tests** verify the **internal machinery** — hook dispatch, checkpoint creation, shadow branch management, condensation, rewind, session state transitions, etc. — with full control over inputs and deterministic behavior. They cover edge cases like mid-session commits, trailer removal, amend workflows, multi-session interleaving, and concurrent session conflicts.\\n\\n**E2E tests** verify the **end-to-end contract** — \\\"if I give Claude a prompt, does the right file get created, does the checkpoint get saved, does rewind work?\\\" They validate that the real agent + real hooks + real CLI all wire together correctly. The test names (`scenario_checkpoint_workflows_test.go`, `scenario_rewind_test.go`, `scenario_basic_workflow_test.go`) reflect this scenario-level scope.\\n\\n`★ Insight ─────────────────────────────────────`\\n- This is a classic **test pyramid** structure. Integration tests form the wide middle layer (fast, deterministic, thorough coverage of internal logic), while E2E tests form the narrow top (slow, expensive, but validate the full system wiring). The build tag separation (`integration` vs `e2e`) lets CI run the cheap tests on every push while keeping expensive agent calls opt-in.\\n- The `HookRunner` pattern in integration tests is a form of **test double at the process boundary** — rather than mocking Go interfaces, it feeds crafted JSON to the real CLI binary via stdin. This tests the actual binary's hook parsing without needing a live agent, c